        {
            "id": "intro_loops",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "While Loops",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 1
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "Sometimes you need to do the same thing multiple times. Instead of writing the same code over and over, you can use **loops** to repeat code automatically."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "A `while` loop repeats code as long as a condition is `True`. It's like saying \"keep doing this while this condition is true.\""
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "basic_while_loop",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "heading",
                    "content": "Basic While Loop",
                    "properties": {
                        "level": 2
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "A `while` loop starts with `while`, followed by a condition, then a colon `:`. The code that repeats is indented."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "The loop checks the condition before each repetition. If the condition is `True`, it runs the code inside the loop. If the condition is `False`, it stops and continues with the rest of your program."
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "In the code below, the `while` loop will run until the condition `count <= 3` is `False`, printing the numbers 1, 2, and 3."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "count = 1\nwhile count <= 3:\n    print(f\"Count: {count}\")\n    count = count + 1",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "Count: 1\nCount: 2\nCount: 3"
                    }
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "infinite_loop_warning",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "**Be careful!** If the condition never becomes `False`, the loop will run forever. This is called an **infinite loop** and can crash your program."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "basic_while_loop",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "If you take a closer look inside the while loop, you'll see that the `count` variable is being updated by adding 1 to it. This eventually will make the condition `count <= 3` become `False`, and the loop will stop. This is very important to avoid infinite loops."
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "count = 1\nwhile count <= 3:\n    print(f\"Count: {count}\")\n    count = count + 1",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python",
                        "output": "Count: 1\nCount: 2\nCount: 3"
                    }
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "infinite_loop_example",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "**The Infinite Loop**"
                },
                {
                    "type": "code",
                    "content": "count = 1\nwhile count <= 3:\n    print(f\"Count: {count}\")\n    # Missing: count = count + 1",
                    "properties": {
                        "language": "python"
                    }
                },
                {
                    "type": "text",
                    "content": "In this broken code, since we are not updating the `count` variable inside the loop, it stays 1 forever, so `count <= 3` is always `True`, and the loop never stops!"
                }
            ]
        },
